LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;background-color:aqua;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The Company is currently subject to an audit by U.S. Customs&nbsp;&amp; Border Protection ("CBP") in respect of the period from 2006 to 2010. In October 2013, CBP issued the final audit report. In that report CBP projects that unpaid duties totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$12.4</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;million are due for the period under review and recommends collection of the duties due. Crocs responded that these projections are erroneous and provided arguments that demonstrate the amount due in connection with this matter is considerably less than the projection. Additionally, on December&nbsp;12, 2014, Crocs made an offer to settle CBP's potential claims and tendered </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$3.5</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;million. At this time, it is not possible to determine how long it will take CBP to evaluate Crocs' offer or to predict whether Crocs' offer will be accepted. Likewise, if a settlement cannot be reached, it is not possible to predict with any certainty whether CBP will seek to assert a claim for penalties in addition to any unpaid duties, but such an assertion is a possibility.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Crocs is currently subject to an audit by the Brazilian Federal Tax </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Authorities related to imports of footwear from China between 2010 and 2014. On January&nbsp;13, 2015, Crocs was notified about the issuance of assessments totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$4.0</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;million for the period January 2010 through May 2011. Crocs has disputed these assessments and asserted defenses to the claims. On February&nbsp;25, 2015, Crocs received additional assessments totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$9.3</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;million related</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to the remainder of the audit period. Crocs has also disputed these assessments and asserted defenses and filed an appeal to these claims. It is anticipated that this matter will take up to several years to be resolved. It is not possible at this time to predict the outcome of this matter.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> REVOLVING CREDIT FACILITY &amp; BANK BORROWINGS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 11pt;text-indent: -11pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Senior Revolving Credit Facility</font> </p> <p inline;color:#000000;"> 2011, Crocs entered into an Amended and Restated Credit Agreement (as amended, the "Credit Agreement"), with the lenders named therein and PNC Bank, National Association ("PNC"), as a lender and administrative agent for the lenders.</font><a name="gmnh1page_fq14601_1_27"></a><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> On February&nbsp;18, 2016, the Company entered into the Eleventh Amendment to the Amended and Restated Credit Agreement which</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, primarily</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">: (i)&nbsp;extended the maturity date to February, 2021, (ii)&nbsp;resized the borrowing capacity of the facility to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$75.0</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;million, (iii)&nbsp;amended certain definitions of the financial covenants to become more favorable to the Company, (iv)&nbsp;set the minimum fixed charge coverage ratio to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">1.00</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to 1.00 </font><font style="display: inline;">through the period ended June&nbsp;30, 2016 and </font><font style="display: inline;">1.10</font><font style="display: inline;"> to 1.00 thereafter, (v)&nbsp;set the maximum leverage ratio to </font><font style="display: inline;">2.50</font><font style="display: inline;"> to 1.00 through the period ended June&nbsp;30, 2016 and </font><font style="display: inline;">2.00</font><font style="display: inline;"> to 1.00 thereafter, (vi)&nbsp;allows up to </font><font style="display: inline;">$50.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million in stock repurchases to be made each fiscal year, subject to certain restrictions, and (vii)&nbsp;limited certain capital expenditures and commitments to an aggregate of </font><font style="display: inline;">$50.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million per year. Under the terms of the agreement, the above financial covenants are only applicable when borrowings exceed an average of </font><font style="display: inline;">$18.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million over a </font><font style="display: inline;">30</font><font style="display: inline;">-day period, starting on the 15</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:5pt;vertical-align:super;line-height:100%">th</font><font style="display: inline;"> of the last month of each quarter. The Eleventh Amendment also changed the variable lending rate. For domestic</font><font style="display: inline;"> base</font><font style="display: inline;"> rate loans, including swing loans, the interest rate is equal to a daily base rate plus a margin ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;">0.50%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">0.75%</font><font style="display: inline;"> based on certain conditions. For </font><font style="display: inline;">domestic</font><font style="display: inline;"> LIBOR rate loans, the interest rate is equal to a LIBOR rate plus a margin ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;">1.50%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">1.75%</font><font style="display: inline;"> based on certain conditions. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of March&nbsp;31, 2016, the Company was in compliance with each of these covenants: (i) </font><font style="display: inline;">the</font><font style="display: inline;"> fixed charge coverage ratio was </font><font style="display: inline;">3.94</font><font style="display: inline;"> to 1.00, compared to the minimum covenant requirement of 1.00 to 1.00 (ii) </font><font style="display: inline;">the</font><font style="display: inline;"> leverage ratio was </font><font style="display: inline;">0.37</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">1</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font><font style="display: inline;">0</font><font style="display: inline;">0, </font><font style="display: inline;">compared to the maximum covenant requirement of </font><font style="display: inline;">2.50</font><font style="display: inline;"> to 1.00 (iii) stock repurchases were </font><font style="display: inline;">zero</font><font style="display: inline;">, and (iv) capital expenditures and commitments were </font><font style="display: inline;">$11.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million. For the three months ended March 31, 2016, the weighted average/effective interest rate for outstanding senior revolving credit facility</font><font style="display: inline;"> borrowings was </font><font style="display: inline;">4.0%</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of March 31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company had </font><font style="display: inline;">$8.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">zero</font><font style="display: inline;">, respectively, of outstanding borrowings under the Credit Agreement. As of both March 31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company had outstanding letters of credit of </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.3</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, which were reserved against the borrowing base under the terms of the Credit Agreement. As of March 31, 2016 and December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company had </font><font style="display: inline;">$65.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$73.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, of available borrowing capacity. During the three months ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, Crocs capitalized </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.6</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million in fees and third party costs as deferred financing costs associated with the negotiation of a new debt financing agreement</font><font style="display: inline;"> that has not yet been executed</font><font style="display: inline;">. style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 11pt;text-indent: -11pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Asia Pacific Revolving Credit Facility</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On August&nbsp;28, 2015, a Crocs subsidiary entered into a revolving credit facility agreement with HSBC Bank (China) Company Limited, Shanghai Branch ("HSBC") as the lender. The revolving credit facility enables Crocs to borrow uncommitted dual currency revolving loan facilities up to RMB </font><font style="display: inline;">40.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, or the USD equivalent, and import facilities up to RMB </font><font style="display: inline;">60.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, or the USD equivalent, with a combined facility limit of RMB </font><font style="display: inline;">60.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million. This revolving credit facility supports possible future net working capital needs in China. For loans denominated in USD, the interest rate is </font><font style="display: inline;">2.1%</font><font style="display: inline;"> per annum plus LIBOR for three months or any other period as may be determined by HSBC at the end of each interest period. For loans denominated in RMB, interest equals the </font><font style="display: inline;">one</font><font style="display: inline;"> year benchmark lending rate effective on the loan drawdown date set forth by the People's Bank of China with a </font><font style="display: inline;">10%</font><font style="display: inline;"> mark-up and is payable on the maturity date of the related loan. The revolving credit facility is guaranteed by Crocs,&nbsp;Inc. The revolving credit facility can be canceled or suspended at any time at the discretion of the lender and contains provisions requiring Crocs</font><a name="gmnh1page_fq14601_1_28"></a><font style="display: inline;"> to maintain compliance with certain restrictive covenants. As of March 31, 2016 and December 31, 2015, the revolving credit facility remained temporarily suspended at the discretion of the lender and Crocs had </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> outstanding borrowings under the revolving credit facility. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 11pt;text-indent: -11pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Long-term Bank Borrowings</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">On December&nbsp;10, 2012, Crocs entered into a Master Installment Payment Agreement ("Master IPA") with PNC in which PNC financed the Company's implementation of a new ERP system, which began in October 2012 and was substantially completed in early 2015. The terms of each note payable, under the Master IPA, consist of a fixed interest rate and payment terms based on the amount borrowed and the timing of activity throughout the implementation of the ERP system. The Master IPA is subject to cross-default, cross-termination</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> clauses</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, and is coterminous with the Credit Agreement.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">As of March 31, 2016 and December 31, 2015 Crocs had $</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">5.0&nbsp;million and $6.4</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;million, respectively, of debt outstanding under </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">five</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> separate notes payable, of which </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$4.2</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;million and </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$4.8</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;million, respectively, represent current installments. As of March 31, 2016, the notes bear interest rates ranging </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">from </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2.45%</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2.79%</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">and maturities ranging from September 2016 to September 2017. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The components of the Company&#x2019;s consolidated debt and capital lease obligations are as follows:</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse;width: DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Crocs transacts business in various foreign countries and is therefore exposed to foreign currency exchange rate risk inherent in revenues, costs, and monetary assets and liabilities denominated in non-functional currencies. In general, Crocs enters into foreign currency exchange forward contracts and currency swap derivative instruments to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreign currency exchange rates. As these derivative instruments do not qualify as hedging instruments under the accounting standards for derivatives and hedging, they are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value recognized in 'Foreign currency transaction </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">gain (</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">loss</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">)</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, net' in the </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">consolidated statements of operations. For purposes of the cash flow statement, Crocs classifies the cash flows from derivative instruments at settlement from undesignated instruments in the same category as the cash flows from the related hedged items, generally within 'Cash provided by (used in) operating activities'.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The following table summarizes the notional amounts of outstanding foreign currency exchange contracts as of March 31, 2016 and December 31, 2015. The notional amounts of the derivative financial instruments shown below are denominated in their U.S. Dollar equivalents and represent the amount of all contracts of the foreign currency specified. These notional values do not necessarily represent amounts exchanged by the parties and, therefore, are not a direct measure of the Company's exposure to the foreign currency exchange risks.</font> As of March 31, 2016, the unvested RSUs are expected to be amortized over the remaining weighted average period of </font><font style="display: inline;">2.21</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;years, which consists of a remaining weighted average period of </font><font style="display: inline;">2.23</font><font style="display: inline;"> years related to performance-based awards and a remaining weighted average period of </font><font style="display: inline;">2.19</font><font style="display: inline;"> years related to time-based awards.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 3000000 3000000 -0.08 0.07 -0.08 0.07 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per Share</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in any form. The Company&#x2019;s Series A convertible preferred stock (&#x201C;Series A preferred stock&#x201D;) issued in 2014 represents participating securities as holders of the Series A preferred stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of the Company&#x2019;s non-vested restricted stock and restricted stock unit awards are</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in the Company&#x2019;s earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security, if any, is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above. This method assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS</font><font style="display: inline;">. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note 11&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">. FAIR VALUE MEASUREMENTS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recurring Fair Value Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">GAAP provides for a fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to the valuation techniques used to measure fair value into three broad levels. Level 1 inputs are quoted market prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities that the reporting entity has the ability to access at the measurement date. Level 2 inputs are inputs other than quoted market prices included within Level 1 that are observable for the asset or liability, either directly or indirectly. Level 3 inputs are unobservable inputs for the asset or liability.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of March 31, 2016 and December 31, 2015, our assets subject to fair value measurements consisted solely of cash equivalents of </font><font style="display: inline;">$7.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">$7.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, which are Level 1 assets</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, and foreign currency derivative </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">assets</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> of </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$1.3</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">million and </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">liabilities of </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$0.1</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">million, respectively, which are L</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">evel 2 assets. The Company's Level </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">1 assets are classified in the </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">consolidated balance sheets as 'Cash and cash equivalents' and 'Prepaid expenses </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">and other assets'. </font><font style="display: inline;">As of March 31, 2016 and December 31, 2015</font><font style="display: inline;">, t</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">he Level </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2 assets</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> or liabilities</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> are classified in the </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">consolidated balance sheets as </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#x2018;</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Prepaid expenses and other assets</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#x2019; and </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">'Accrued expenses and other liabilities'</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, respectively</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Non-Recurring Fair Value Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The majority of the Company&#x2019;s non-finan</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">cial instruments, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">inventories, property and equipment, and intangible assets, are</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> Level 3 assets and are</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. However, if certain triggering events occur such that a non-financial instrument is required to be evaluated for impairment and the carrying value is not recoverable, the carrying value would be adjusted to the lower of its cost or fair value and an impairment charge would be recorded. During the three months ended March 31, 2016, Crocs recorded </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.2</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million in impairment charges associated with the Company&#x2019;s retail locations.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During the three months ended </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">March 31, 2015</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> the Company had no impairment charges </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">associated wit</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">h the Company&#x2019;s retail locations or inventory write-down charges.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 95882000 3498000 5135000 82596000 4016000 637000 100462000 3723000 5219000 86771000 4113000 636000 9350000 14233000 10943000 13210000 14812000 16792000 177882000 3498000 6892000 162700000 4016000 776000 179802000 3723000 6879000 164451000 4113000 636000 82000000 1757000 80104000 139000 79340000 1660000 77680000 1300000 100000 494000 -1247000 1751000 5613000 -5723000 -3509000 1973000 2611000 500000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">4. style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Stock Compensation</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In March 2016, the Financial Accounting Standards Board ("FASB") issued Accounting Standards Update ("ASU") No. 2016-09, </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Compensation &#x2013; Stock Compensation (Topic 718),</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> which is intended to increase simplification of accounting for equity share-based payment transactions, including the income tax consequences, classification of awards as either eq</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">u</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ity or liabilities, and classification on the statement of cash flows.</font><font style="display: inline;"> In addition, the amendments in this </font><font style="display: inline;">update</font><font style="display: inline;"> eliminate the guidance in Topic 718 that was indefinitely deferred shortly after the issuance of FASB Statement No. 123 (revised 2004), Share-Based Payment.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">This standard is effective for annual periods (including interim periods) b</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">eginning after December 15, 2016</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, with early adoption permitted. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Amendments related to the timing of when excess tax benefits are recognized, minimum statutory withholding requirements, forfeitures, and intrinsic value should be applied using a modified retrospective transition method by means of a cumulative-effect adjustment to equity as of the beginning of the period in which the guidance is adopted. Amendments related to the presentation of employee taxes paid on the statement of cash flows when an employer withholds shares to meet the minimum statutory withholding requirement should be applied retrospectively. Amendments requiring recognition of excess tax benefits and tax deficiencies in the income statement and the practical expedient for estimating expected term should be applied prospectively. An entity may elect to apply the amendments related to the presentation of excess tax benefits on the statement of cash flows using either a prospective transition method or a retrospective transition method. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The C</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ompany is currently assessing the impact of adoption of this standard on the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Prepaid Stored-Value Products</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">In March 2016, the FASB issued ASU No. 2016-04,</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;font-style:italic;">Liabilities - Extinguishment of Liabilities (Subtopic 405-20): Recognition of Breakage for Certain Prepaid Stored-Value </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;font-style:italic;">Product</font><a name="T2"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;font-style:italic;">s.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;"> This update </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">aligns</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;"> recognition of the financial liabilities related to prepaid stored-value products (for example, prepaid gift cards), with Topic 606,</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;font-style:italic;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers,</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">for non-financial liabilities. In general, certain of these liabilities may be extinguished proportionally in earnings as redemptions occur, or when redemption is remote if issuers are not entitled to the unredeemed stored value. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">This standard is effective for annual periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 201</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">7</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, with early adoption permitted. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">At adoption, this update will be applied either </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">using a modified retrospective transition method by means of a cumulative-effect adjustment to retained earnings as of the beginning of the fiscal year in w</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">hich the guidance is effective or a</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;"> retrospectively to each period presented.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;"> The Company is currently assessing the adoption method and the impact that adopting this new accounting standard will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">L</font><font style="display: inline;">eases</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <a name="ST1104665501"></a><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">In February 2016, the </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">FASB</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> issued </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">ASU</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> No. 2016-02, </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">Leases (Topic 842),</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> which is intended to increase transparency and comparability of accounting for lease transactions. This update revises accounting for operating leases by a lessee, among other changes, and requires a lessee to recognize a liability to make lease payments and an asset representing its right to use the underlying asset for the lease term in the balance sheet. The distinction between finance and operating leases has not changed and the update does not significantly change the effect of finance and operating leases on the statement of operations. This standard is effective for annual periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2018, with early adoption permitted. At adoption, this update will be applied using a modifi</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">ed retrospective approach. The C</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">ompany is currently assessing the impact of adoption of this standard on the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Financial Instruments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In January 2016, the FASB issued ASU 2016-01:&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Financial Instruments&#x2014;Overall: Recognition and Measurement of Financial Assets and Financial Liabilities.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> The pronouncement requires equity investments (except those accounted for under the equity method of accounting, or those that result in consolidation of the investee) to be measured at fair value with changes in fair value recognized in net income, requires public business entities to use the exit price notion when measuring the fair value of financial instruments for disclosure purposes, requires separate presentation of financial assets and financial liabilities by measurement category and form of financial asset, and eliminates the requirement for public business entities to disclose the method(s) and significant assumptions used to estimate the fair value that is required to be disclosed for financial instruments measured at amortized cost. These changes become effective for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2017. The expected adoption method of ASU 2016-01 is being evaluated by the Company and the adoption is not expected to have a significant impact on the Company's condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Inventory</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In July 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-11:&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, which modifies existing requirements regarding measuring inventory at the lower of cost or market. Specifically, this standard eliminates the need to determine and consider replacement cost or net realizable value less an approximately normal profit margin when measuring inventory. This standard is effective prospectively after December&nbsp;15, 2016, with early adoption permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Debt Issuance Costs</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In April 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-03:&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs,</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> which requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability, consistent with debt discounts. ASU&nbsp;2015-03 requires retrospective adoption and is effective for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2015. </font><a name="P261302862"></a><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In August 2015, the FASB issued </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ASU 2015-15:&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Interest &#x2013; Imputation of Interest (Subtopic 835-30),</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> which relates to the presentation of debt issuance costs associated with line-of-credit arrangements. This standard clarifies the guidance set forth in FASB ASU 2015-03, which requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be presented on the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the debt liability rather than as an asset. The new pronouncement clarifies that debt issuance costs related to line-of-credit arrangements</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;color:#000000;"> could continue to be presented as an asset and be subsequently amortized over the term of the line-of-credit arrangement, regardless of whether there are any outstanding borrowings on the arrangement. Crocs considered this clarification in conjunction with the adoption of FASB ASU 2015-03, which occurred during the three months ended March 31, 2016. These pronouncements do not have a material impact on the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial statements. In adopting ASU 2015-15, Crocs elected to present debt issuance costs related to line-of-credit arrangements as an asset.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Share-Based Payments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In June 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-12 in response to the EITF consensus on Issue 13-D. The ASU clarifies that entities should treat performance targets that can be met after the requisite service period of a share-based payment award as performance conditions that affect vesting. Therefore, an entity would not record compensation expense related to an award for which transfer to the employee is contingent on the entity's satisfaction of a performance target until it becomes probable that the performance target will be met. The ASU does not contain any new disclosure requirements. This ASU is effective for all entities for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2015. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;color:#000000;">During the three months ended March 31, 2016, Crocs adopted this pronouncement, which does not have a material impact on the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU 2014-09:&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that "an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services." ASU 2014-09 becomes effective for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2017. Early application is permitted for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2016. This new standard permits the use of either the retrospective or cumulative effect transition method. Crocs is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">its</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> condensed consolidated financial statements. Crocs has not yet selected a transition method or determined the effect of the standard on financial reporting once the standard is effective.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Other new pronouncements issued but not effective until after </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">March </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">31, 2016 are not expected to have a material impact on the Company's </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">condensed consolidated financial statements</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 3 -2362000 -5403000 -37910000 40951000 15378000 17335000 8238000 14243000 -6074000 -28633000 48950000 16576000 25851000 6523000 2077000 2129000 24812000 22456000 26830000 24524000 59000 61000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">ORGANIZATION &amp; Stock Compensation (Topic 718),</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> which is intended to increase simplification of accounting for equity share-based payment transactions, including the income tax consequences, classification of awards as either eq</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">u</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ity or liabilities, and classification on the statement of cash flows.</font><font style="display: inline;"> In addition, the amendments in this </font><font style="display: inline;">update</font><font style="display: inline;"> eliminate the guidance in Topic 718 that was indefinitely deferred shortly after the issuance of FASB Statement No. 123 (revised 2004), Share-Based Payment.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">This standard is effective for annual periods (including interim periods) b</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">eginning after December 15, 2016</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, with early adoption permitted. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Amendments related to the timing of when excess tax benefits are recognized, minimum statutory withholding requirements, forfeitures, and intrinsic value should be applied using a modified retrospective transition method by means of a cumulative-effect adjustment to equity as of the beginning of the period in which the guidance is adopted. Amendments related to the presentation of employee taxes paid on the statement of cash flows when an employer withholds shares to meet the minimum statutory withholding requirement should be applied retrospectively. Amendments requiring recognition of excess tax benefits and tax deficiencies in the income statement and the practical expedient for estimating expected term should be applied prospectively. An entity may elect to apply the amendments related to the presentation of excess tax benefits on the statement of cash flows using either a prospective transition method or a retrospective transition method. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The C</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ompany is currently assessing the impact of adoption of this standard on the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Prepaid Stored-Value Products</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">In March 2016, the FASB issued ASU No. 2016-04,</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;font-style:italic;">Liabilities - Extinguishment of Liabilities (Subtopic 405-20): Recognition of Breakage for Certain Prepaid Stored-Value </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;font-style:italic;">Product</font><a name="T2"></a><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;font-style:italic;">s.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;"> This update </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">aligns</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;"> recognition of the financial liabilities related to prepaid stored-value products (for example, prepaid gift cards), with Topic 606,</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;font-style:italic;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers,</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">for non-financial liabilities. In general, certain of these liabilities may be extinguished proportionally in earnings as redemptions occur, or when redemption is remote if issuers are not entitled to the unredeemed stored value. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">This standard is effective for annual periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 201</font><font style="display: style="display: inline;">L</font><font style="display: inline;">eases</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <a name="ST1104665501"></a><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">In February 2016, the </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">FASB</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> issued </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">ASU</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> No. 2016-02, </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">Leases (Topic 842),</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> which is intended to increase transparency and comparability of accounting for lease transactions. This update revises accounting for operating leases by a lessee, among other changes, and requires a lessee to recognize a liability to make lease payments and an asset representing its right to use the underlying asset for the lease term in the balance sheet. The distinction between finance and operating leases has not changed and the update does not significantly change the effect of finance and operating leases on the statement of operations. This standard is effective for annual periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2018, with early adoption permitted. At adoption, this update will be applied using a modifi</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">ed retrospective approach. The C</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">ompany is currently assessing the impact of adoption of this standard on the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Financial Instruments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In January 2016, the FASB issued ASU 2016-01:&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Financial Instruments&#x2014;Overall: Recognition and Measurement of Financial Assets and Financial Liabilities.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> The pronouncement requires equity investments (except those accounted for under the equity method of accounting, or those that result in consolidation of the investee) to be measured at fair value with changes in fair value recognized in net income, requires public business entities to use the exit price notion when measuring the fair value of financial instruments for disclosure purposes, requires separate presentation of financial assets and financial liabilities by measurement category and form of financial asset, and eliminates the requirement for public business entities to disclose the method(s) and significant assumptions used to estimate the fair value that is required to be disclosed for financial instruments measured at amortized cost. These changes become effective for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2017. The expected adoption method of ASU 2016-01 is being evaluated by the Company and the adoption is not expected to have a significant impact on the Company's condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Inventory</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In July 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-11:&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, which modifies existing requirements regarding measuring inventory at the lower of cost or market. Specifically, this standard eliminates the need to determine and consider replacement cost or net realizable value less an approximately normal profit margin when measuring inventory. This standard is effective prospectively after December&nbsp;15, 2016, with early adoption permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Debt Issuance Costs</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In April 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-03:&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs,</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> which requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability, consistent with debt discounts. ASU&nbsp;2015-03 requires retrospective adoption and is effective for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2015. </font><a name="P261302862"></a><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In August 2015, the FASB issued </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ASU 2015-15:&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Interest &#x2013; Imputation of Interest (Subtopic 835-30),</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> which relates to the presentation of debt issuance costs associated with line-of-credit arrangements. This standard clarifies the guidance set forth in FASB ASU 2015-03, which requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be presented on the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the debt liability rather than as an asset. The new pronouncement clarifies that debt issuance costs related to line-of-credit arrangements</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;color:#000000;"> could continue to be presented as an asset and be subsequently amortized over the term of the line-of-credit arrangement, regardless of whether there are any outstanding borrowings on the arrangement. Crocs considered this clarification in conjunction with the adoption of FASB ASU 2015-03, which occurred during the three months ended March 31, 2016. These pronouncements do not have a material impact on the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial statements. In adopting ASU 2015-15, Crocs elected to present debt issuance costs related to line-of-credit arrangements as an asset.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Share-Based Payments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In June 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-12 in response to the EITF consensus on Issue 13-D. The ASU clarifies that entities should treat performance targets that can be met after the requisite service period of a share-based payment award as performance conditions that affect vesting. Therefore, an entity would not record compensation expense related to an award for which transfer to the employee is contingent on the entity's satisfaction of a performance target until it becomes probable that the performance target will be met. The ASU does not contain any new disclosure requirements. This ASU is effective for all entities for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2015. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;color:#000000;">During the three months ended March 31, 2016, Crocs adopted this pronouncement, which does not have a material impact on the Company&#x2019;s condensed consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU 2014-09:&nbsp; </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that "an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services." ASU 2014-09 becomes effective for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2017. Early application is permitted for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2016. This new standard permits the use of either the retrospective or cumulative effect transition method. Crocs is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">its</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> condensed consolidated financial statements. Crocs has not yet selected a transition method or determined the effect of the standard on financial reporting once the standard is effective.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Other new pronouncements issued but not effective until after </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">March </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">31, 2016 are not expected to have a material impact on the Company's </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">condensed consolidated financial statements</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> Accounts receivable are recorded at invoiced amounts, net of reserves and allowances, and do not bear interest. Crocs uses its best estimate to determine the required allowance for doubtful accounts based on a variety of factors including the length of time receivables are past due, economic trends and conditions affecting the Company's customer base and historical collection experience. Specific provisions are recorded for individual receivables when the Company becomes aware of a customer's inability to meet its financial obligations. </font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">4</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">. OPERATING SEGMENTS AND GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Crocs has </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> reportable operating segments based on the geographic nature of the Company&#x2019;s operations: Americas, Asia Pacific, and Europe. Crocs&#x2019; &#x201C;Other businesses&#x201D; category aggregates insignificant operating segments that do not meet the reportable segment threshold and includes manufacturing operations located in Mexico,&nbsp;Italy and Asia. The composition of the Company&#x2019;s reportable operating segments is consistent with that used by Crocs&#x2019;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> chief operating decision maker</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> (&#x201C;CODM&#x201D;) to evaluate performance and allocate resources.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Each of the reportable operating segments derives its revenues from the sale of footwear and accessories to external customers as well as intersegment sales. Revenues of the 'Other businesses' category are primarily made up of intersegment sales. The remaining revenues for 'Other businesses' represent non-footwear product sales to external customers. Intersegment sales are not included in the measurement of segment operating income or regularly reviewed by the CODM and are eliminated when deriving total consolidated revenues.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Segment performance is evaluated based on segment results without allocating corporate expenses, or indirect general, administrative, and other expenses. Segment profits or losses include adjustments to eliminate intersegment sales. As such, reconciling items for segment operating income represent unallocated corporate and other expenses as well as intersegment eliminations. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p inline;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following tables set forth information related to Crocs&#x2019; reportable operating business segments as of and for the three months ended March 31 2016 and 2</font><font style="display: inline;">015:</font> </p> <p with share-based compensation, research and development, brand marketing, legal, restructuring, depreciation and amortization of corporate and other assets not allocated to operating segments and costs of the same nature related to certain corporate holding companies.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> The decrease in &#x2018;Unallocated corporate and other&#x2019; operating 3333 438939 6500000 100000 5700000 100000 15.00 13.00 11.80 467241 1295749 791561 14.09 15.90 4.19 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">2. SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per Share</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in any form. The Company&#x2019;s Series A convertible preferred stock (&#x201C;Series A preferred stock&#x201D;) issued in 2014 represents participating securities as holders of the Series A preferred stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of the Company&#x2019;s non-vested restricted stock and restricted stock unit awards are</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in the Company&#x2019;s earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security, if any, is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above. This method assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS</font><font style="display: inline;">. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note 11&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Asset Impairments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Crocs periodically evaluates all of its long-lived assets for impairment when events or circumstances would indicate the carrying value of a long-lived asset may not be fully recoverable. </font><font style="display: inline;">The following table summarizes retail asset impairment charges by reportable operating segment for the three months ended March 31, 2016 and 2015 related to certain underperforming stores that were unlikely to generate sufficient cash flows to fully recover the carrying value of the stores&#x2019; assets over the remaining economic life or lease terms of those assets:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:1pt;">&#xFEFF;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Accounts receivable are recorded at invoiced amounts, net of reserves and allowances, and do not bear interest. Crocs uses its best estimate to determine the required allowance for doubtful accounts based on a variety of factors including the length of time receivables are past due, economic trends and conditions affecting the Company's customer base and historical collection experience. As the interest rate of each credit agreement is variable, typically based on either the base rate plus an additional margin or the daily LIBOR rates plus an additional margin, the estimated fair value of each debt instrument approximates its carrying value. Carrying value represents the weighted average interest rate in effect at March 31, 2016 for all borrowings outstanding pursuant to each debt instrument, including any applicable margin. The interest rates presented represent stated rates and do not include the impact of the derivative instruments, deferred financing costs, original issue premiums or discounts, and commitment fees, all of which affect Crocs' overall cost of borrowing. Unused borrowing capacity represents the maximum available under the applicable facility at March 31, 2016 without regard to covenant compliance calculations or other conditions precedent to borrowing. On February 18, 2016, the Company entered into the Eleventh Amendment to the Amended and Restated Credit Agreement, which extended the maturity date to February 2021, resized the borrowing capacity of the facility to $75.0 million, and amended certain definitions of the financial covenants to become more favorable to the Company. As of March 31, 2016, the unused borrowing capacity was reduced by $8.5 million of outstanding borrowings and $1.3 million of outstanding letters of credit. Increase of $8.5 million is primarily due to the combined impact of: (i) a $4.7 million increase in revenues, (ii) a $2.2 million decrease in selling, general and administrative expenses, primarily associated with decreases in commissions and marketing expenses, and (iii) a $1.8 million decrease in restructuring charges. Minimum rentals include all lease payments as well as fixed and variable common area maintenance, parking and storage fees, which were approximately $2.5 million and $2.3 million during the three months ended March 31, 2016 and 2015, respectively The amounts in 'Other' consist of various accrued expenses, of which no individual item accounted for more than 5% of the total balance as of March 31, 2016 or December 31, 2015.
